english:
  title: Preface to the Account of Eoph진사's Filial Piety
  author: Lee Cheom
  language: eng
  text: Filial piety is the source of all virtuous conduct. A person becomes filial only when they have properly nourished their parents in life and arranged their funeral with fitting dignity, thereby fulfilling the way of serving one's parents. In caring for them, there shines a countenance of joy and warmth; at their passing, a face etched with sorrow and grief; in performing rituals, a bearing of reverence and propriety. These expressions emanate from the heart and manifest upon the face. Though joy, sorrow, and reverence differ in appearance, they spring from the same root—love for one's parents. Only by fulfilling all that is due to parents can one be called truly benevolent. As Youzi once said, "Filial piety and respect for elder brothers—are these not the foundation of benevolence?" In truth, when a person dwells in poverty, it is difficult enough to sustain their parents in life; far more arduous is the careful observance of funeral rites and ancestral commemoration. In ancient times, few among the poor could fully accomplish such duty toward their parents, and how much less in this present age? Among those who have studied at my school—whether they have entered official service, devoted themselves to literature, or remained humble in straitened circumstances—all know this truth. There is one surnamed Fish, called Bokhae, born in the remote borderlands and raised in a modest farmstead. By nature he is circumspect and magnanimous, firm of purpose, unmoved by glory or gain. In all his actions he follows propriety and law. Upon maturity, he attended the village school, studied the classics and refined his learning, and came to understand something of the teachings of poetry, history, benevolence, and righteousness. In serving his parents, he never failed in morning and evening inquiries, in providing warmth in winter and coolness in summer, in offering nourishing foods suited to their taste. When they passed away, he wailed and lamented both morning and evening, never allowing himself to smile. When he established their family shrine and made seasonal offerings, he kindled in his heart the profound sense of reverence for the departed. Surely such a one can be said to have fulfilled the way of serving one's parents. The customs of that remote region favor martial prowess and do not honor learning and virtue. When they witnessed this display, they were startled, yet soon found themselves moved to follow his example. Thus did his conduct awaken and transform them all, each now seeking to emulate his virtue. For all people possess an innate conscience; seeing something worthy of imitation, they naturally follow it, just as grass and trees unfold their blossoms when their season comes, growing abundantly though they know not why. If only those simple folk of the borderlands would take filial piety as their model, and transform it into loyalty to the sovereign and service to the state for the welfare of the people—would not such virtue, rooted in filial devotion, bring boundless benefit to all? Zengzi taught, "When the end is honored and the past remembered, the people's virtue becomes abundant." His words ring true. I stand as teacher to this worthy man. If I know of his exemplary conduct yet remain silent, I lack discernment. If I know it yet fail to speak, I am wanting in benevolence. Therefore I venture to praise his deeds and present them to the Keeper of Records, that his merit might be recognized and his distinction marked. Yet such honors are neither his wish nor within my power to grant.
  footnotes:
    - 'Youzi (有子): A disciple of Confucius, known for his teachings on filial piety and virtue.'
    - 'Zengzi (曾子): Another prominent Confucian sage and disciple of Confucius, famous for his emphasis on personal moral cultivation.'
    - 'Fish Bokhae (魚覆河): The subject of this preface, a man of humble origins whose filial piety inspired moral transformation in his community.'
    - The reference to 'establishing a family shrine' reflects the Confucian emphasis on ancestor veneration as central to filial piety.
